  "summary": "George, posing as a doctor, arrives at Morrow House with a young man carrying the limp body of Frankie (Frances Downton) following her staged car accident. They are greeted by an older butler and Mrs. Baskington-French, a tall woman with red hair and light blue eyes. George places Frankie in a first-floor bedroom overlooking the garden. While the young man describes the accident to the household, George and Frankie whisper privately. George expresses concern that his professional reputation might be harmed if the true nature of the accident is revealed, but Frankie reassures him. To avoid the need for further medical intervention, George instructs Frankie to pretend she is a follower of Christian Science.\n\nGeorge informs the homeowner that Frankie has a mild concussion and requires rest. He identifies her as Miss Frances Downton, noting her connection to the DeReauks, and claims he will manage her family notifications and the car repairs. During her stay, Frankie feels guilty about her deception, particularly as she develops a friendship with Mrs. Baskington-French. While the hostess appears calm and family-oriented, Frankie observes a hint of underlying worry in her eyes. Frankie also meets the owner, a friendly but absent-minded man, and his seven-year-old son, Tommy. Mrs. Baskington-French mentions that her brother-in-law, Roger, a charming but restless man who struggles to hold a job, is expected to visit the following day.",
